			<section class="lessonInfoSection">
				<p class="lessonText">A <span>Scale</span> is a sequence of certain notes within an octave. The first kind of scale we will go over is the <span>Major Scale</span>.</p><br>
				<p class="lessonText">Any major scale can be created by using a formula. The formula tells us when to make whole and half steps so that it creates a major scale.</p>
				<img src="../images/lesson7/majorFormula.jpg" alt="major scale formula">
				<p class="lessonText">W's represent whole steps, and h's respresent half steps. We'll build a C Major Scale as an example. The starting note is a C.</p>
				<img src="../images/lesson7/c1.jpg" alt="first note in c major scale">
				<p class="lessonText">Following the formula, we make a whole step to D.</p>
				<img src="../images/lesson7/c2.jpg" alt="second note in c major scale">
				<p class="lessonText">We take another whole step to E</p>
				<img src="../images/lesson7/c3.jpg" alt="third note in c major scale">
				<p class="lessonText">Then a half step to F</p>
				<img src="../images/lesson7/c4.jpg" alt="fourth note in c major scale">
				<p class="lessonText">Now we go back to a whole step for the next note, G.</p>
				<img src="../images/lesson7/c5.jpg" alt="fifth note in c major scale">
				<p class="lessonText">From G we go up another whole step to A.</p>
				<img src="../images/lesson7/c6.jpg" alt="sixth note in c major scale">
				<p class="lessonText">From A we go a whole step up to B.</p>
				<img src="../images/lesson7/c7.jpg" alt="seventh note in c major scale">
				<p class="lessonText">And lastly from B, we take the last half step up back to C.</p>
				<img src="../images/lesson7/c8.jpg" alt="back to c in the major scale">
				<p class="lessonText">No matter what note you start on, as long as you follow the formula you create a major scale.</p>
				<hr class="hr">

				<p class="lessonText">The next type of scale we will go over is the <span>Minor Scale</span>.</p><br>
				<p class="lessonText">Any minor scale can be created by using this formula. We'll build an A Natural Minor Scale for this example.</p>
				<img src="../images/lesson7/minorFormula.jpg" alt="minor scale formula">
				
				<p class="lessonText">The first note of course is A.</p>
				<img src="../images/lesson7/a1.jpg" alt="first note in minor scale">
				<p class="lessonText">From A we take a whole step up to B.</p>
				<img src="../images/lesson7/a2.jpg" alt="second note in minor scale">
				<p class="lessonText">From B we immediately switch it up and take a half step up to C.</p>
				<img src="../images/lesson7/a3.jpg" alt="third note in minor scale">
				<p class="lessonText">After C, we go back to a whole step, up to D.</p>
				<img src="../images/lesson7/a4.jpg" alt="fourth note in minor scale">
				<p class="lessonText">We then go another whole step up to E.</p>
				<img src="../images/lesson7/a5.jpg" alt="fifth note in minor scale">
				<p class="lessonText">Switch back to a half step, up to F.</p>
				<img src="../images/lesson7/a6.jpg" alt="sixth note in minor scale">
				<p class="lessonText">And then back to a whole step up to G.</p>
				<img src="../images/lesson7/a7.jpg" alt="seventh note in minor scale">
				<p class="lessonText">Finally we take another whole step back to an A.</p>
				<img src="../images/lesson7/a8.jpg" alt="back to a note in minor scale">
				<p class="lessonText">These are the two main types of scales in music, but there are also other scales that are variations of the two main types.</p>
				<hr class="hr">

				<p class="lessonText">The last subject we will discuss in this lesson are <span>Key Signatures</span>. Key Signatures show you every accidental that appears in a scale.</p><br>
				<p class="lessonText">Instead of writing sharps and flats next to each note, you can specify the the key signature at the beginning of the measure.</p>
				<img src="../images/lesson7/keySig.jpg" alt="example key signature">
				<p class="lessonText">For this example, the accidentals at the beginning of the measure tell you that every note on that line or space will be sharp. The notes in this scale contain <span>C#</span>, <span>F#</span>, and <span>G#</span>.</p><br>

